# Chapter 3 â€” Forms

A form is a piece of Scheme source. Every form either evaluates to a value or performs a side effect. This chapter walks every special form the language ships.

## `define`

Binds a name in the current scope.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define pi 3.14159)
pi
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (square x) (* x x))
(square 9)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (compose f g) (lambda (x) (f (g x))))
((compose square (lambda (n) (+ n 1))) 4)
</pre>

## `let`, `let*`, `letrec`

Local bindings. `let` evaluates every RHS before binding any name. `let*` sees earlier bindings. `letrec` allows mutual recursion.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(let ((x 3) (y 4)) (+ (* x x) (* y y)))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(let* ((x 3) (y (* x x))) y)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(letrec ((even? (lambda (n) (if (= n 0) #t (odd? (- n 1)))))
         (odd?  (lambda (n) (if (= n 0) #f (even? (- n 1))))))
  (even? 10))
</pre>

## `lambda`

Builds a function value.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
((lambda (x) (* x x)) 12)
</pre>

## `if`, `cond`, `when`, `case`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(if (> 3 2) 'yes 'no)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(cond ((= 1 2) 'never)
      ((= 1 1) 'first-match)
      (else    'fallthrough))
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(when (> 5 0) (display \"positive\") (newline))
</pre>

## `quote`, `quasiquote`, `unquote`

`'x` = `(quote x)`. Backtick + comma let you splice a computed value into a quoted template.

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
'(a b c)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(let ((n 4)) `(square is ,(* n n)))
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> If you remember one thing from this chapter â€” `define`, `lambda`, `if`, and `let` cover ninety percent of the code you'll ever write. The rest is sugar or specialization.

